sec.p:
Our approach is slightly different. As commonly used, the term “reputation” combines two aspects of prospective buyers’ knowledge of the seller that are theoretically separable: (1) how much prospective buyers know about the seller and (2) whether what they know is good or bad. To measure the extent to which the available information indicates that the seller is good or bad, we use NEGPCT = (# of negative responses)/(
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $n+1$ \end{document}
               ), wheren= (# of positive responses + # of negative responses).8Obviously we expect the price to be negatively related to NEGPCT. As a measure of how much buyers know about the seller, we use
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{STDDEV}\,=[ 1/ ( n+1) ] ^{.5}$ \end{document}
               . When the number of feedbacks is small, NEGPCT provides a very imprecise measure of the true percentage for a particular seller. As the number of feedbacks increases, NEGPCT should become a more reliable measure of the seller’s trustworthiness and service. This is particularly true since the percentage of negative feedbacks is small. For 94% of the sales in our sample, NEGPCT is .025 or less, so a NEGPCT figure based on, say, 10 feedbacks does not provide much information to distinguish between most of our sellers. The variable STDDEV is our measure of the uncertainty surrounding NEGPCT. If π is the true likelihood of a bad experience, the standard deviation of the sample proportion of bad experiences is
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $[ \pi ( 1-\pi ) ] ^{.5}$ \end{document}
               . Thus for a given π, the standard deviation of the proportion of bad experiences is proportional to
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $( 1/ n) ^{.5}$ \end{document}
               . To avoid division by zero in the case of sellers with no prior feedbacks, we approximate this as
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $[ 1/ ( n+1) ] ^{.5}$ \end{document}
               . So in summary, NEGPCT measures the proportion of reported bad experiences for the seller, and STDDEV is a measure of how uncertainty about this proportion as measured by the standard deviation declines as the number of feedbacks increases.9We expect both NEGPCT and STDDEV to have negative coefficients. InSection Vbelow, we also model reputation in a Bayesian framework in which buyers start with a prior probability of a bad experience that is updated as additional information about the seller is received.

fn.p:
It should be emphasized that STDDEV is a measure of how the standard deviation changes as the number of feedbacks increases and is not a measure of the standard deviation itself, which also depends on the proportion of bad experiences π. We do not include a measure of π in STDDEV since (1) NEGPCT already captures this aspect, and (2) if one substitutes the sample proportionpfor the unknown population proportion π, the standard deviation is not
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $[ p( 1-p) / n] ^{.5}$ \end{document}
                     but a more complicated expression that is undefined for smalln(Stuart and Ord1987).

sec.p:
Since negative feedbacks are relatively rare, NEGPCT would seem to provide little information when the number of feedbacks is small. While the percentage of negative feedbacks for our sample is 0.52%, in a sample of, say, 19 feedbacks, NEGPCT must be 0%, 5%, 10%, and so forth. Consequently, we would expect bidders to place less weight on NEGPCT when its standard deviation is high because the number of feedbacks on which it is based is low. This implies that if we add an interaction term NEGPCT×STDDEV to the regression, its coefficient should be greater than zero. However, when we add such as interaction term toequation (1), it is significant (
                  \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $t=-.10$ \end{document}
               ) and its coefficient is negative. In other words, there is no evidence that bidders place less importance on NEGPCT when it is based on just a few feedbacks.

fn.p:
Since the dependent variable is in log from, the estimated percentage impact of certification on the price in nonlog terms is
                        \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $\mathrm{exp}\,( \beta _{1}) -1$ \end{document}
                     .

sec.p:
Certification and grade.—One question is whether the impact of third‐party certification differs by claimed grade. The specification inequation (1)forces thepercentageimpact of certification to be the same regardless of the grade. While this means that the dollar impact is higher at the higher grades, the percentage impact might also differ. If a comic is assigned a grade of poor, then it should matter little whether the comic is certified or not since it could not be graded lower. At the other extreme (as we explore below), a very high noncertified grade, such as near‐mint, might be especially suspect since (as Jin and Kato [2002] point out) the apparent dollar payoff to certification is higher at the higher grades. To test whether the percentage impact of certification differs by grade, we add a set of interaction terms (CERT i ×GRADE ji ), yielding the revised equation:
