Since the estimates of bothaandbare fairly small, the implication is that buyers place very low weight on their prior probabilities versus new information in calculating posterior probabilities. According to the estimates intable 4, if a seller has only one prior feedback, the average buyer gives the prior a weight of .246 and the single feedback a weight of .754 in calculating her posterior probability. After only three prior feedbacks, the average buyers places a weight of only .098 on her original prior and a weight of .902 on the sample ratio of negative to total feedbacks. After 10 prior feedbacks, the prior receives a weight of only 3.2%. As shown intable 4, the parameter
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $a+b$ \end{document}
            has a fairly high standard error (and the null that the prior receives a weight of zero cannot be rejected). However, the upper limit of a 95% confidence interval for
               \documentclass{aastex} \usepackage{amsbsy} \usepackage{amsfonts} \usepackage{amssymb} \usepackage{bm} \usepackage{mathrsfs} \usepackage{pifont} \usepackage{stmaryrd} \usepackage{textcomp} \usepackage{portland,xspace} \usepackage{amsmath,amsxtra} \usepackage[OT2,OT1]{fontenc} \newcommand\cyr{ \renewcommand\rmdefault{wncyr} \renewcommand\sfdefault{wncyss} \renewcommand\encodingdefault{OT2} \normalfont \selectfont} \DeclareTextFontCommand{\textcyr}{\cyr} \pagestyle{empty} \DeclareMathSizes{10}{9}{7}{6} \begin{document} \landscape $a+b$ \end{document}
            would be only 1.63, which would still imply that buyers’ priors receive very little weight relative to the sample evidence, even if the number of feedbacks reported is quite small. These implied weights for the buyers’ priors relative to the sample information seem unrealistically small and at variance with our results for the STDDEV variable. Since negative feedbacks are rare (less that 1% in our sample), the informational content of only a few feedbacks should be fairly low. Our results for the STDDEV variable indicate that the number of feedbacks has an important impact on the price received, whereas these results imply that the incremental impact of additional feedbacks fades out rapidly. This question of how much weight bidders place on the feedback information vis‐à‐vis their a priori expectations is an interesting avenue for future research.

